@Database HBBSMultiTop

@Node Main "HBBSMultiTop.Guide"

  HBBSMultiTop
  ============

   This utility is a program to create stats and listings of various
   things, e.g. Top Uploaders, Downloaders, Callers etc.

   It takes a template file (see hbbs:utils/hbbsmultitop_mts/#?.mt for
   examples) and parses it to create an output file.

   You can make it parse several input files and create several output files
   at the same time.

   PLEASE READ ALL OF THIS FILE TO GAIN BEST USE FROM THIS PROGRAM!!

   Usage
   =====

   HBBSMultiTop [<in-template> <out-ansi>...]

   e.g  say you had a .mt file called topup.mt and another called topdown.mt
   you could use:

     HBBSMultiTop topup.mt topup.txt topdown.mt topdown.txt

   It would then create the two output files called topup.txt and
   topdown.txt


   Template Files
   ==============

   The template (.mt) files are very similar in format to HBBS Screen files,
   apart from the following differences:

     * The file need not start with @^@, but if it contains @^@ codes that
       HBBSMultiTop does not recognise it should.

     * @^@ sequences that are not recognised by HBBSMultitop CAN be used
       but will be left as they appear (i.e. they will not be stripped)
       This is so that when HBBS displays the screen file the remaining
       @^@ codes will be displayed!  Oh my god, just how cool is this...


   Fields you can specify
   ======================

     TBUH = top bytes uploader handle
     TBUB = top bytes uploader bytes
     TBUF = top bytes uploader files
     TBUG = top bytes uploader group

     TBDH = top bytes downloader handle
     TBDB = top bytes downloader bytes
     TBDF = top bytes downloader files
     TBDG = top bytes downloader group

     TFUH = top files uploader handle
     TFUB = top files uploader bytes
     TFUF = top files uploader files
     TFUG = top files uploader group

     TFDH = top files downloader handle
     TFDB = top files downloader bytes
     TFDF = top files downloader files
     TFDG = top files downloader group

     TMWH = top message writer handle
     TMWB = top message writer bytes
     TMWF = top message writer messages

     BCUH = Best CPS Up Handle
     BCUG = Best CPS Up Group
     BCUC = Best CPS Up CPS

     BCDH = Best CPS Down Handle
     BCDG = Best CPS Down Group
     BCDC = Best CPS Down CPS


     TCH = top caller handle
     TCB = top caller bytes
     TCC = top caller calls

     TBU  = Total Bytes Uploaded
     TFU  = Total Files Uploaded
     TBD  = Total Bytes Downloaded
     TFD  = Total Files Downloaded

     TC   = Total Calls
     TM   = Total Messages

     BCU  = Best Ever CPS Up
     BCD  = Best Ever CPS Down

     * more to come!

   Examples screen files
   =====================

   ---- cut here ----

   Top Five Uploaders!

     @^-15.15^TBUH@ @^-20.20^TBUG@ with @^10.10^TBUB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBUF@ files
     @^-15.15^TBUH@ @^-20.20^TBUG@ with @^10.10^TBUB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBUF@ files
     @^-15.15^TBUH@ @^-20.20^TBUG@ with @^10.10^TBUB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBUF@ files
     @^-15.15^TBUH@ @^-20.20^TBUG@ with @^10.10^TBUB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBUF@ files
     @^-15.15^TBUH@ @^-20.20^TBUG@ with @^10.10^TBUB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBUF@ files

   ---- cut here ----

   The above example would look like this:

     Top Five Uploaders!

       Hydra           [=- dAT'97 -=]       with  108645968 bytes in  358 files
       mR pINk         Real Time Recording  with   19730211 bytes in   73 files
       wizdom          data division!       with   10935548 bytes in   36 files
       [-CJA-]         [-hELLFiRE-]         with    1261781 bytes in    6 files
       MoRv            no                   with    1000000 bytes in      files


   Notice that each time TBUH is used the user next in the list of top byte
   uploaders will be used the next time TBUH is specified..
   The same applies to TBDH, TFUH etc... (???H)

   Also notice that the user MoRv had not uploaded any files but has been
   awarded 1MB free creds..

   Example of a MultiChart
   =======================

   You can also mix charts together, unlike all other multi top generators!

   Here we mix top byte downloaders with top message writers in the same
   template file.

   Only HBBSMultiTop can do this:

   ---- cut here ----

   Top Three Leechers!

     @^-15.15^TBDH@ / @^-20.20^TBDG@ with @^10.10^TBDB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBDF@ files
     @^-15.15^TBDH@ / @^-20.20^TBDG@ with @^10.10^TBDB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBDF@ files
     @^-15.15^TBDH@ / @^-20.20^TBDG@ with @^10.10^TBDB@ bytes in @^4.4^TBDF@ files

   Kewlest message writers!

     @^-15.15^TMWH@ / @^-20.20^TMWG@ with @^10.10^TMWM@ messages
     @^-15.15^TMWH@ / @^-20.20^TMWG@ with @^10.10^TMWM@ messages
     @^-15.15^TMWH@ / @^-20.20^TMWG@ with @^10.10^TMWM@ messages

   Stats:

      Total Bytes Up   @^-10.10^TBU@   Total Files Up   @^TFU@
      Total Bytes Down @^-10.10^TBD@   Total Files Down @^TFD@

   ---- cut here ----



   Of course, you're not limited to doing 3 or 5 users at a time..  you can use
   the paramaters as many times as you like!

   You can mix ansi escape sequences in the file as well, but not within @^@'s
   (obviously!).

   If you use (say) "TBUH" 22 times in a file and you only have 20 users, the
   last two TBU?'s are replaced with blanks.

   For further print format specification details see @{"Screens.Guide" link HBBS:Docs/Reference/Screens.guide/Main}

   You must use a TBUH either first or last because if you used the following
   paramaters in this order: @^TBUG@ @^TBUB@ @^TBUH@ @^TBUF@
   You'd find that it does not work very well as the first three TBU?'s
   would be from the Number 1 Top Byte Uploader, then the TBUF would be from
   the 2nd best Top Byte Uploader.

   Note:
   =====

   HBBS's "Control" program *must* be running or HBBSMultitop will pause
   until control is started and then fail.

   Kewl:
   =====

   Try running:

   "HBBS:Utils/HBBSMultiTop HBBS:Utils/HBBSMultiTop.guide ram:test.guide"

   And then open ram:test.guide in multiview or amigaguide to see the
   above examples with the results
   filled in!!

@EndNode



